%N A389359 Triangle read by rows: T(n,0) = 1, T(n,n) = n+1 and T(n,k) = T(n, k-1) + T(n-1, k-1) + T(n-2, k-1) +1 for 0 < k < n.
%C A389359 A similar triangle is defined by J. M. Bergot in the comments of A211278, using the same T(n,0) and T(n,n) but without the +1 term in the recurrence.
%C A389359 For large enough n, T(n, k) stabilizes and becomes constant. The triangle converge column wise to A003462(n+1): for n >= 2k, T(n, k) = (3^(k+1) - 1)/2.
%H A389359 Paolo Xausa, <a href="/A389359/b389359.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 0..11475</a> (rows 0..150 of triangle, flattened).
%F A389359 T(n+1, n) = 2*A211278(n) - (n+1).
%F A389359 T(n+2, n) = 2*A383527(n+1) - (n+3).
%F A389359 T(n, floor(n/2)) = A052993(n).
%F A389359 Sum_{k=0..n} T(2*n, k) = A000340(n).
%e A389359 Triangle T(n, k) starts:
%e A389359 n\k :     0       1       2        3        4       5       6      7      8
%e A389359 ============================================================================
%e A389359  0  :     1
%e A389359  1  :     1       2
%e A389359  2  :     1       4       3
%e A389359  3  :     1       4      11        4
%e A389359  4  :     1       4      13       28        5
%e A389359  5  :     1       4      13       38       71       6
